orically problematic; it is also at odds with Sachs's generally cyclical poetic process. In "The Space of Words," Jennifer Hoyer offers the first sustained critical analysis of Sachs's largely unanalyzed prewar poetry and prose, as well as the first analysis that examines structural and thematic ties between the prewar works and the Nobel Prize-winning postwar poetry. Through close readings of both Sachs's prewar and postwar works, Hoyer reveals a diasporic rather than exilic conception of the landscape of language, a position of constant wandering rather than static longing for return. This diasporic poetics promotes the intellectual and linguistic power of the wanderer and opens new insights into Sachs's essentialsignificance as a Holocaust poet and a twentieth-century German-Jewish writer wary of the link of literary language to geopolitics and the narrative of nations. Jennifer M. Hoyer is Assistant Professor of German at theUniversity of Arkansas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aEnglish studies.  aGerman studies.  aHolocaust poets.  aJewish studies.  aNelly Sachs.  aholocaust.  alanguage studies.  alanguage.  alinguistics.  amodern history.  amodern poetry.  apoetry.  apostwar poetry.  atwentieth century.  aworld history.  aworld war II.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113874340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571138743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571138743/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles